<p><b>Chris Anderson</b> (born July 9, 1961)<sup id="cite_ref-Curr_Bio_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Curr_Bio-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> is an American author. He was with <i>The Economist</i> for seven years, then joining <i><a href="Wired_(magazine)" title="Wired (magazine)">WIRED</a></i> magazine in 2001 where he was the editor-in-chief until 2012. He is known for his 2004 article entitled <i><a href="The_Long_Tail" title="The Long Tail" class="mw-redirect">The Long Tail</a></i>; which he later expanded into the 2006 book, <i>The Long Tail: Why the Future of Business Is Selling Less of More</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-BAnderson2006_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BAnderson2006-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> He is the co founder and chairman of 3DRobotics, a robotic manufacturing company.<sup id="cite_ref-DIYD_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DIYD-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
